{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518577"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:06:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:06:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12936"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12936"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.66,0.05,0.1,0.06,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5374"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48795"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5374"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12936"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33760"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1780"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9798"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10261"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13001"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48795"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of fatigue, weight loss, and night sweats. On examination, his pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 120/78 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, temperature 38.7 \u00b0C, and SpO2 99% on room air. He has an enlarged spleen, palpable 8 cm below the costal margin. Enlarged lymph nodes are palpable in the cervical, axillary, and inguinal regions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe laboratory findings are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 90 g/L (135 \u2013 180)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean corpuscular volume (MCV): 82 fL (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite Cell Count (WCC): 60*10^9/L (4.0 \u2013 11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeutrophils: 1.5*10^9/L (1.8 \u2013 7.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELymphocytes: 51.9*10^9/L (1.0 \u2013 3.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMonocytes: 0.6*10^9/L (0.2 \u2013 0.8)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEosinophils: 0.5*10^9/L (0.02 \u2013 0.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets: 57*10^9/L (150 \u2013 450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ECG shows no significant abnormalities and a chest X-ray shows no signs of cardiac or pulmonary involvement. Abdominal ultrasound and CT scan show significant splenomegaly, consistent with the physical examination findings. There are no other abdominal abnormalities noted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFurther investigations show that the circulating lymphocytes are found to express CD5, CD19, CD20, CD200, and CD23 without CD79a or CD10.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following may be seen on the peripheral blood smear in this case?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Smudge cells","Pencil cells","Target cells","Dacryocytes","Schistocytes"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has chronic lymphocytic leukaemia (CLL). The condition begins with the development of a monoclonal population of B-lymphocytes (monoclonal B-cell lymphocytosis). Subsequently, these lymphocytes expand and accumulate in the lymphoid tissue, peripheral blood, and bone marrow. As a result, generalised painless lymphadenopathy, hepatosplenomegaly, and cytopenia are commonly observed. Patients may also present with constitutional symptoms including fatigue, fever, night sweats, early satiety, and unintentional weight loss. Hypogammaglobulinaemia can develop in up to two-thirds of patients, increasing the risk for infectious complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmudge cells\u003C/strong\u003E are lymphocytes that have been damaged when a peripheral blood smear is made. Due to the fragility of lymphocytes in CLL, smudge cells are often a prominent feature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPencil cells\u003C/strong\u003E are abnormally elongated and hypochromic erythrocytes, typically seen in individuals with iron deficiency anaemia. In addition, microcytosis and hypochromia are commonly seen in iron deficiency. These features are not consistent with the case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETarget cells\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as codocytes or bull\u0027s-eye cells, have a central area of increased colour (haemoglobin) surrounded by a lighter ring and another darker outer ring. Target cells can be seen in iron deficiency anaemia, thalassaemia, or haemoglobinopathy, but they are not associated with CLL.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDacryocytes\u003C/strong\u003E, or teardrop cells, are erythrocytes with a distorted teardrop shape. They can be seen in myelofibrosis and other bone marrow infiltrative disorders. The presence of lymphadenopathy, marked lymphocytosis, and the flow cytometry findings in this case are not consistent with myelofibrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESchistocytes\u003C/strong\u003E are fragmented erythrocytes, a feature of microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia (MAHA). The causes of MAHA include thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura, atypical haemolytic uremic syndrome, and disseminated intravascular coagulation. The clinical picture and laboratory findings in the case presented are not consistent with these conditions, and schistocytes are not a characteristic feature of CLL.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Smudge cells are lymphocytes that have been damaged when a peripheral blood smear is made.","In chronic lymphocytic leukaemia, smudge cells are often a prominent feature.","Other clinical and laboratory features of chronic lymphocytic leukaemia are lymphocytosis, lymphadenopathy, hepatosplenomegaly, cytopenia, and constitutional symptoms."],"references":["Shadman M. Diagnosis and Treatment of Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia: A Review. JAMA. 2023;329(11):918-32.","Julio D, Ferran N, Dolors C, Elias C. Chronic lymphocytic leukemia: from molecular pathogenesis to novel therapeutic strategies. Haematologica. 2020;105(9):2205-17."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33760"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12936"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33760"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-16T21:38:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-16T21:39:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5374"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48795"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCoun